<div id="review_3438844794" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3438844794" />
    <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus"><img alt="Settare (on hiatus)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590610257p2/13198822.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3438844794?book_show_action=true">Oct 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Settare (on hiatus)" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus">Settare (on hiatus)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141182711" href="/book/show/863768.The_Waves">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=virginia">virginia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=penguin-classics-wishlist">penguin-classics-wishlist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=women-writers">women-writers</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=modern-classics">modern-classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=british-irish">british-irish</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=english-literature">english-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=wishlist">wishlist</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3438844794" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15672513759586439381">The Waves is a stunning piece of writing that flows seamlessly through the entire lives of six characters, combining together thoughts, ideas, feelings, identities, time, and space, in an undulating stream of magnificent prose. <br/><br/>I struggle to find words eloquent enough to describe my reading experience of Woolf&apos;s lyrical masterpiece. I waited for a week to let it all sink in, I finally forced myself to sit down to write my thoughts, I got up, I paced up and down the room, came back, repeated this</span>
  <span id="freeText15672513759586439381" style="display:none">The Waves is a stunning piece of writing that flows seamlessly through the entire lives of six characters, combining together thoughts, ideas, feelings, identities, time, and space, in an undulating stream of magnificent prose. <br /><br />I struggle to find words eloquent enough to describe my reading experience of Woolf's lyrical masterpiece. I waited for a week to let it all sink in, I finally forced myself to sit down to write my thoughts, I got up, I paced up and down the room, came back, repeated this a few times, and eventually decided that I simply cannot talk about The Waves the way I do about other, more conventional, less striking books. <br /><br />Writing about The Waves is like attempting to describe music, memory, threads of thought, corporeal perceptions, or consciousness. No words, descriptions, or reviews can convey the full experience of melting in and flowing with Woolf's words. Instead, I will take refuge in what I can write about: personal lived experience, and try to compare that to <i>The Waves</i>. <br /><br />I am very fond of nature. My most favorite natural phenomena are mountains, sunrises, and ocean waves (<i>The Waves</i> is filled with beautiful, vivid imagery of the sun and waves, making it significantly more enjoyable for me on a personal level). I also like to talk about adventures in the outdoors or take pictures of natural surroundings. But there's one very specific memory that I've never been able to adequately capture in words. <br /><br />I once went on a sunrise surfing trip with some friends. We paddled a few hundred meters into the Indian ocean, and calmly sat on our boards waiting for waves to catch. My surfing skills are practically non-existent, so I just sat on my board nonchalantly, watching the experienced people catch the waves and ride to the shore with a hint of envy, breathing in the early morning air, completely aware of my surroundings, completely aware of the moment and <i>here and now</i>. <br />I floated there, slightly detached from the others, but still in their presence. Suddenly, strokes of sunshine splashed all over us and over the waves, and the sun rose into the sky. There was a brilliant, almost blinding light in my eyes as I tried to savor the view. I remember wishing I could hold on to that moment, wishing I could stop time and relish at that moment for eternity. That is my most cherished, most vivid memory of life, the one and the only experience I wish I could have captured in a photograph (if only I had a GoPro!), could have documented, could have saved and kept safe somewhere outside the perishable cellular chambers of my brain. But I couldn't. And I've always felt a sense of longing toward that moment, that brief, glorious moment that I lived and had to let go of. I reckoned that moment was gone.<br />Until I read The Waves. The Waves, to me, was the embodiment of that moment, the manifestation of all my memories and sensations from that single moment into words. Reading it is as if I've been given a high-quality documentary movie from that scene. As if someone's given me back the memory in solid form. So this book is a personal treasure. A book that will, aside from its intrinsic beauty, literary value and historic impact, always remind me of the bittersweet awareness of visceral, momentary joy in life. <br /><br />That's it. An ultimate favorite, and an unforgettable read. Thank you, Virginia. <br /><br /><br />First impressions right after finishing the book:<br />I am speechless and thunderstruck. I might’ve just finished my favorite piece of fiction, ever.<br />Review to come after it sinks in and when I can gather my thoughts and articulate them into words.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15672513759586439381" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


