    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3270835118" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3270835118" />
    <a title="Chavelli Sulikowska" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska"><img alt="Chavelli Sulikowska" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1534643154p2/16127160.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3270835118?book_show_action=true">Apr 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chavelli Sulikowska" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chavelli Sulikowska" href="/user/show/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska">Chavelli Sulikowska</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska?shelf=five-star">five-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/16127160-chavelli-sulikowska?shelf=favourite-authors">favourite-authors</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3270835118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4738754536140012691">I’ll say it again, no one writes like Virginia Woolf. No author, living or dead comes even close to her level of creative genius with the English language. While all Woolf’s novels are spectacular, the Waves is her ultimate legacy, and more than one hundred years on it remains unparalleled in it’s pertinence, unequalled in its beauty. Everyone should commit themselves to reading the Waves at least once in a lifetime. <br/><br/>It requires concerted dedication, concentration, and cogitation. But you will b</span>
  <span id="freeText4738754536140012691" style="display:none">I’ll say it again, no one writes like Virginia Woolf. No author, living or dead comes even close to her level of creative genius with the English language. While all Woolf’s novels are spectacular, the Waves is her ultimate legacy, and more than one hundred years on it remains unparalleled in it’s pertinence, unequalled in its beauty. Everyone should commit themselves to reading the Waves at least once in a lifetime. <br /><br />It requires concerted dedication, concentration, and cogitation. But you will be richly rewarded if you submit yourself to the challenging sublimity of the language. Granted, reading it’s a bit like being cast out at sea, in a row boat without oars, at the mercy of the ocean, the rocking of the waves and then finally the welcomed calmness of the tide. You will be confused, frustrated, a little lost, have lot’s of “aha” moments, reread entire sections and muse over meanings (if there were any). <br />Like all great works of art, an enormous amount of effort has gone in to constructing what seems like a seamless, very fluid novel. Of course, Woolf’s skill is her capacity to achieve a style that is so elegant and effortless, pure bliss to read. The prose is magnificent, it has a soft, quilt like, poetic cadence, a rise and fall. It is almost mystical, ethereal, abstractly powerful. “How then does light return to the world after the eclipse of the sun? Miraculously. Frailly. In thin stripes. It hangs like a glass cage. It is a hoop to be fractured by a tiny jar. There is a spark there. Next moment a flush of dun. Then a vapour as if earth were breathing in and out, once, twice, for the first time. Then under the dullness someone walks with a green light. Then off twists a white wraith. The woods throb blue and green, and gradually the fields drink in red, gold, brown. Suddenly a river snatches a blue light. The earth absorbs colour like a sponge slowly drinking water. It puts on weight; rounds itself; hangs pendent; settles and swings beneath our feet.” <br /><br />Rather than plot driven or character focused, the Waves is a truly sensory experience. It’s pleasurable in the way a Summer afternoon of wine tasting is (when you’re not doing the driving). You may feel a little heady, slumberous, unfocused as you read. It is emotive and aims to provoke our sensations rather than clearly deduct tangible meaning (though Woolf manages to infuse meaning also, it is secondary to the emphasis on sensation). <br /><br />So there is not much action or dependence on drama, the Waves shifts in focus over time, place and has multiple narrators – it can be disorienting as the changes are subtle, however, there is always a return to the sea and the momentum of the waves which provides both the touch plate for the story and more importantly, the rhythm for the entire novel. “The waves broke and spread their waters swiftly over the shore. One after another they massed themselves and fell; the spray tossed itself back with the energy of their fall. The waves were steeped deep-blue save for a pattern of diamond-pointed light on their backs which rippled as the backs of great horses ripple with muscles as they move. The waves fell; withdrew and fell again, like the thud of a great beast stamping.”<br /><br />There are six friends, Bernard, Susan, Rhoda, Neville, Jinny and Louis through whom Woolf casts her nostalgic narrative. A seventh friend, Percival is referenced only, but he is equally integral to the story. The seashore, deafened by the thrashing of the waves, is where the story begins with the characters meeting as children, it is where they meet again as adults, mourning the death of Percival. The passing of time in between – school, college, careers, parenthood, is also rendered through the continuum and rhythmic movement of the waves – constant and unrelenting, rising and falling with life’s ups and downs. Woolf herself notes that she writes to a rhythm and not a plot, so the use of waves to symbolise the passage of time is not only an effective language tool, it is also dramatic and evocative.<br /><br />The character’s monologues (sometimes it is unclear where one left off and the other picked up), are deeply personal. It is like being in their thoughts on a minute by minute basis, and here there is no better choice than Woof’s penchant for stream of consciousness writing. It is through these personalised accounts that we really get to know the characters, their hopes and fears, ambitions and regrets, desires and jealousies. They are both self critical and critically aware of each other, completely tuned in to the actions and reactions of their personalities. Indeed, they only exist in relation to one another, “I am not one and simple, but complex and many,” and are forever bound together by their hero love of Percival and their collective grief over his sudden death…. “For this moment, this one moment, we are together. I press you to me. Come, pain, feed on me. Bury your fangs in my flesh. Tear me asunder. I sob, I sob.”<br /><br />All the characters have different personalities, they all have foibles and self doubts and inadequacies, wishing to be more than they are, chasing their dreams but accepting ultimately who they become. All this is reflected on deeply, but ultimately cast aside in their joint mourning of Percival, the revered one, their hero, perfect in death because in death we can make no mistakes. “There was no freedom in life, and certainly there was none in death…”<br /><br />There is reminiscence, memories flood like the tide and their emotions crash like the waves. In this regard, the characters and their experiences are just tools Woof uses to extrapolate what I think is her point – that life is hard but we live it, we must, for there is nothing else we can do, except die. And then death, well, that’s clearly very final. “I need silence, and to be alone and to go out, and to save one hour to consider what has happened to my world, what death has done to my world.” But as much as it is about death, it is very much a book about life and living and self discovery: “I have made up thousands of stories; I have filled innumerable notebooks with phrases to be used when I have found the true story, the one story to which all these phrases refer. But I have never yet found the story. And I begin to ask, Are there stories?”<br /><br />Some would call Woolf’s writing experimental. It is and it isn’t - there is no real experiment here, no testing evident. She is very deliberate and her premise is clear. It is ground breaking modernist literature, that is undeniable, but not experimental. There are so many erudite passages I may as well have highlighted the whole novel! “Let us again pretend that life is a solid substance, shaped like a globe, which we turn about in our fingers. Let us pretend that we can make out a plain and logical story, so that when one matter is despatched—love for instance—we go on, in an orderly manner, to the next. ” I could cite many more, but instead, I implore you to read it for yourselves.<br /><br />Upon finishing, this novel anchors in your heart. The rhythm of Woolf’s words on the waves is permanent, even a century later. “The moment was all; the moment was enough.” It is unforgettable.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4738754536140012691" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


