    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2507602659" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2507602659" />
    <a title="MihaElla " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36408043-mihaella"><img alt="MihaElla " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1596985417p2/36408043.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2507602659?book_show_action=true">Aug 26, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="MihaElla " class="user" itemprop="url" name="MihaElla " href="/user/show/36408043-mihaella">MihaElla </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9789731034393" href="/book/show/17914035-valurile">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2507602659" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8391618702834852662">I was looking forward eagerly to opening the first page of the next V.W. book after Orlando gave me high hopes that nothing is impossible. According to my one week vacation plan I picked up two of them. The lucky winner as standing out brightly in the first row was The Waves. Why? Because it started with lines like these: &lt;&lt; The sun had not yet risen. The sea was not separated from the sky; it was only slightly creased, like a bunch of folds. Slowly and slowly, as the sky whitened, a dark line l</span>
  <span id="freeText8391618702834852662" style="display:none">I was looking forward eagerly to opening the first page of the next V.W. book after Orlando gave me high hopes that nothing is impossible. According to my one week vacation plan I picked up two of them. The lucky winner as standing out brightly in the first row was The Waves. Why? Because it started with lines like these: &lt;&lt; The sun had not yet risen. The sea was not separated from the sky; it was only slightly creased, like a bunch of folds. Slowly and slowly, as the sky whitened, a dark line lay on the horizon, separating the sea from the sky ... As it approached the shore, each wave was rising, enriching, shattering, and spreading over the sand a thin layer of white water… &gt;&gt;<br />I read a Romanian translation and although I had no idea how the English text reads and sounds [definitely it should be at least as challenging and complex as the lady author herself] I was glad to acknowledge that the translation is good to better enough. It made my reading struggle smoother and easily flowing in some parts.<br />But the miracle didn’t last too long. After only two pages I started to question my conscience. What have I chosen to read? Is this something comestible or not? Do I get any sense out of it? Not even one single word was sticking to my mind. I was practically unable to read or comprehend even a simple sentence, ordering some words one by one, in a simple logic. The issue was that the opening pages contained some lines of dialogue that had no coherence to each other. At least apparently. There were different voices, speaking out different things, following different elements from surrounding nature. Later on, of course, I made acquaintance with those six characters (three women, three men) who were unfolding some of their life experiences from childhood up to mature years.<br />The reading session started off pretty early in the morning. As I made myself comfortable at my place, cosy bed and straw umbrella, I was telling myself that although I seem pretty much awake still my thinking and reason parts are still very much sleeping. That could happen quite normally during vacation days. You just shut down your mental system for maintenance. But I was eager to have it disquieted. I knew I would get some nice thoughts out of this book reading. Truly so. But I was not ready for such a disheartened start. Will V.W. make my vacation so awfully disquieted? Mentally I was wholly engaged but emotionally I was cold as ice water. Not one inch of my skin was affected even by the sun warming rays.<br />I started to feel discouraged and, simultaneously, I was not willing to admit that maybe I am being defeated by my own choice. So, willing to contradict this state of fact, I immersed more and more into the book. I found out some parts that were speaking as if it was myself actually speaking to myself. Then I started to grow wings. The Waves were taking me far and further away from the shore line. And I was not afraid. I should have been afraid if I was in a practical situation having in mind that I cannot swim, unless helped by some external tools. <br />The body of the novel is basically a continuous alternation between the voices of these six characters, each very individually characterized and so very different from each other. I started to feel myself more interested by diving deeper into these voices and trying to catch the major differences that make each character to be so very particular from the others. I had enjoyed their flights of imagination, their story telling approach when describing their life experiences, struggles, desires, fears and stumbles, their youth dreams on the rising waves of life. It was not easy to go through and keep the pace of reading on a fluid flow. I was tempted to give up at some point. The people around me were having fun, talking and smiling, playing games, while I was reading something that made my wrinkles grew deeper and even new ones were born during this time. Maybe even hair grew a bit whiter. Oh goodness! But I couldn’t give up. I was throwing looks around me saying that I was having my ‘fun time’ too, so no worry, I’ll get there soon enough.<br />One of the characters that talks more than the rest is Bernard. In the closing part of the novel he starts explaining the meaning of his life to the others. And because they seemingly don’t know each other (!) he said he would talk freely. But to be able to make someone comprehend about one’s life, to offer your life in exchange via words, then you have to tell a story; and there are so many stories to be told. Stories from childhood, from schooling years, stories about romantic affairs, about marriage, about death and more and more. And none of them is true.<br />I choose to extract from the book the optimistic perspective towards life. Life is nice. It is a good thing. The simple fact of living is a satisfaction by itself. To be healthy, normal person. To eat, sleep, enjoy clean air, to stroll within lovely alleys, to work actively and fulfilling doing things that enrich your life experience.<br />Yes! Life is nice. <br />Most probably being on vacation made life even nicer. I'm truly grateful for this past!</span>
  <a data-text-id="8391618702834852662" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


